Next Steps:
1. Identify the target Java application and its vulnerability status
2. Check if exploitation was successful by examining response codes and server behavior
3. Block the source IP at the WAF/firewall
4. Search for post-exploitation indicators on the target server
5. Apply security patches for the targeted vulnerability
6. Review Java application configurations for hardening opportunities
7. Implement WAF rules for Java exploitation patterns
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/webserver_generic/web_java_payload_in_access_logs.yml"]', 'exists("log.request") &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
(
  contains("log.request", "getRuntime().exec(") ||
  contains("log.request", "Runtime.getRuntime()") ||
  (contains("log.request", "ProcessBuilder") && contains("log.request", ".start()")) ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)ognl\\.OgnlContext") ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)ognl\\.TypeConverter") ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)ognl\\.MemberAccess") ||
  contains("log.request", "#_memberAccess") ||
  contains("log.request", "struts.valueStack") ||
  (contains("log.request", "multipart/form-data") && contains("log.request", "Content-Disposition") && contains("log.request", ".jsp")) ||
  contains("log.request", "javax.script.ScriptEngineManager") ||
  contains("log.request", "java.lang.ProcessBuilder") ||
  contains("log.request", "java.lang.Runtime") ||
  contains("log.request", "java.net.URLClassLoader") ||
  contains("log.request", "bsh.Interpreter") ||
  contains("log.request", "com.opensymphony.xwork2") ||
  (regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)/wiki/rest/api/") && contains("log.request", "OGNL")) ||
  contains("log.request", "createNativeQuery") ||
  contains("log.request", "javax.el.ELProcessor") ||
  (contains("log.request", "ScriptEngine") && contains("log.request", "eval(")) ||
  contains("log.request", ".class.forName(") ||
  (contains("log.request", "classLoader") && contains("log.request", "getResource"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:03.587566', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-apache-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-nginx-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":3},{"indexPattern":"v11-log-iis-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":3}],"within":"now-15m","count":3}]', '["lastEvent.log.request","adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (226, 'JNDI Exploit Kit Pattern Detected (Log4Shell)', 3, 3, 3, 'Initial Access', 'T1190 - Exploit Public-Facing Application', 'Detects JNDI-Exploit-Kit payload patterns in web server access logs. This includes Log4Shell (CVE-2021-44228) exploitation attempts using JNDI lookup strings targeting LDAP, RMI, DNS, and other protocols. These payloads trigger remote code execution in vulnerable Java applications using Log4j.

Next Steps:
1. Determine if the target application uses a vulnerable version of Log4j
2. Check if the JNDI callback was successful by monitoring outbound LDAP/RMI connections
3. Block the attacker IP and the callback server at the network perimeter
4. Immediately patch Log4j to version 2.17.1 or later
5. Search for successful exploitation indicators on the target host
6. Review all Java applications in the environment for Log4j vulnerabilities
7. Implement WAF rules to block JNDI lookup strings
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/webserver_generic/web_jndi_exploit.yml","https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2021-44228"]', 'exists("log.request") &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)\\$\\{jndi:(ldap|ldaps|rmi|dns|iiop|corba|nds|http)s?://") ||
  contains("log.request", "${jndi:") ||
  contains("log.request", "%24%7Bjndi%3A") ||
  contains("log.request", "${${lower:j}") ||
  contains("log.request", "${${upper:j}") ||
  contains("log.request", "${${::-j}") ||
  (contains("log.request", "${${env:") && contains("log.request", ":-j}")) ||
  contains("log.request", "/Basic/Command/Base64/") ||
  contains("log.request", "/Basic/ReverseShell/") ||
  (contains("log.request", "/Deserialization/") && contains("log.request", "/TomcatBypass/")) ||
  (contains("log.request", "/Deserialization/") && contains("log.request", "/CommonsCollections")) ||
  contains("log.request", "JNDIExploit") ||
  contains("log.request", "JNDI-Injection-Exploit") ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)\\$\\{j\\$\\{[^}]*\\}ndi") ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)\\$\\{\\$\\{[^}]*\\}\\$\\{[^}]*\\}jndi")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:03.727355', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.request","adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (227, 'ModSecurity Rule Violations Detected', 2, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1203 - Exploitation for Client Execution', 'Detects when ModSecurity Web Application Firewall rules are triggered, indicating potential web application attacks or policy violations. This could include SQL injection, XSS, path traversal, or other OWASP Top 10 attack attempts.

Next Steps:
1. Review the specific ModSecurity rule that was triggered and the request details
2. Analyze the blocked request for malicious patterns or payloads
3. Check if this is part of a coordinated attack by reviewing other requests from the same IP
4. Verify that ModSecurity rules are properly tuned to minimize false positives
5. Consider blocking the source IP if confirmed malicious activity
', '["https://www.feistyduck.com/library/modsecurity-handbook-free/online/ch04-logging.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1203/"]', 'exists("origin.ip") &&
exists("log.message") &&
(contains("log.message", "ModSecurity: Warning") ||
 contains("log.message", "ModSecurity: Access denied") ||
 (equals("log.statusCode", 403) && contains("log.message", "mod_security")) ||
 (equals("log.statusCode", 403) && contains("log.message", "ModSecurity")))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:03.881494', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-apache-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":5}]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.path"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (430, 'System Linux: Kernel Module Removal', 1, 3, 3, 'Defense Evasion', 'T1562.001 - Impair Defenses', 'Kernel modules are pieces of code that can be loaded and unloaded into the kernel upon demand. They extend the functionality of the kernel without the need to reboot the system. This rule identifies attempts to remove a kernel module.', '["https://attack.mitre.org/tactics/TA0005/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1562/001/"]', 'regexMatch("log.message", "(modprobe(.+)sudo(.+)(-r|--remove)|modprobe(.+)(-r|--remove)(.+)sudo|sudo(.+)modprobe(.+)(-r|--remove)|sudo(.+)(-r|--remove)(.+)modprobe|(-r|--remove)modprobe(.+)sudo|(-r|--remove)(.+)sudo(.+)modprobe)")', '2026-02-09 16:51:28.567372', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (228, 'ReGeorg Tunneling Webshell Detected', 3, 3, 2, 'Persistence', 'T1505.003 - Server Software Component: Web Shell', 'Detects ReGeorg tunneling webshell command patterns in web server access logs. ReGeorg creates a SOCKS proxy through a web shell, allowing attackers to tunnel arbitrary TCP traffic through a compromised web server. This is commonly used for lateral movement and pivoting within internal networks.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately identify and remove the ReGeorg webshell file from the web server
2. Determine how the webshell was initially deployed (file upload vulnerability, RCE)
3. Analyze network connections tunneled through the webshell
4. Check for lateral movement to internal systems through the tunnel
5. Review web server file integrity for additional webshells
6. Block the attacker''s source IP and any proxy destinations
7. Perform full incident response on the compromised web server
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1505/003/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/webserver_generic/web_webshell_regeorg.yml","https://github.com/sensepost/reGeorg"]', 'exists("log.request") &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
(
  (contains("log.request", "cmd=read") && contains("log.request", "mark=")) ||
  (contains("log.request", "cmd=connect") && contains("log.request", "target=")) ||
  contains("log.request", "cmd=disconnect") ||
  (contains("log.request", "cmd=forward") && contains("log.request", "mark=")) ||
  regexMatch("log.request", "(?i)\\?(cmd|action)=(read|connect|disconnect|forward)&")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:04.007416', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.request","adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (229, 'HTTP Request Smuggling Attempt', 3, 3, 2, 'Initial Access', 'T1190 - Exploit Public-Facing Application', 'Detects potential HTTP request smuggling attempts by identifying malformed requests with multiple Content-Length headers, Transfer-Encoding anomalies, or suspicious protocol versions that may bypass security controls.

Next Steps:
1. Review the full HTTP request logs for the source IP to identify the exact smuggling technique used
2. Check if the request reached backend servers and what response was returned
3. Examine recent requests from the same source IP for patterns or other attack attempts
4. Verify web application firewall and reverse proxy configurations
5. Check for any successful backend requests that bypassed security controls
6. Review authentication logs for the source IP to identify potential account compromise
7. Consider blocking the source IP if confirmed malicious
', '["https://portswigger.net/web-security/request-smuggling","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/"]', '(contains("log.request", "Content-Length") && 
 contains("log.request", "Transfer-Encoding")) ||
(contains("log.request", "\\r\\n\\r\\n") && 
 contains("log.request", "HTTP/")) ||
(exists("log.protoVersion") && 
 !equals("log.protoVersion", "1.0") && 
 !equals("log.protoVersion", "1.1") && 
 !equals("log.protoVersion", "2.0")) ||
(contains("origin.path", "%0d%0a") || 
 contains("origin.path", "%0D%0A")) ||
(contains("log.request", " HTTP/1.1 ") && 
