Next Steps:
1. Review the specific cluster settings that were modified
2. Verify the change was authorized by a cluster administrator
3. Revert unauthorized security setting changes immediately
4. Check if audit logging was disabled during the modification period
5. Review cluster access logs for other suspicious activity
6. Restrict _cluster/settings API access
', '["https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/cluster-update-settings.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1562/"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
(
  (contains("log.message", "_cluster/settings") && (
    contains("log.message", "xpack.security") ||
    contains("log.message", "xpack.monitoring") ||
    contains("log.message", "audit") ||
    contains("log.message", "action.destructive_requires_name")
  )) ||
  (contains("log.message", "cluster settings") && contains("log.message", "updated") && contains("log.message", "security")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "xpack.security.enabled") && contains("log.message", "false")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "xpack.security.audit.enabled") && contains("log.message", "false"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:04.746107', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (234, 'Elasticsearch Bulk Index Deletion Detection', 1, 3, 3, 'Data Destruction', 'T1485 - Data Destruction', 'Detects bulk index deletion operations in Elasticsearch that could indicate data destruction or ransomware attacks targeting cluster data. Monitors for wildcard index deletions and multiple sequential index delete operations.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if the index deletion was authorized
2. Check if the deleted indices can be restored from snapshots
3. Identify the user or API key that performed the deletion
4. Review cluster settings for destructive_requires_name configuration
5. Enable action.destructive_requires_name to prevent wildcard deletions
6. Restrict delete index permissions to administrator roles
', '["https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/indices-delete-index.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1485/"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
(
  (contains("log.message", "delete_index") || contains("log.message", "DeleteIndex")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "indices") && contains("log.message", "deleted")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "DELETE") && regexMatch("log.message", "(?i)/[a-z_*-]+\\s+HTTP")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "index") && contains("log.message", "closed") && contains("log.message", "deleted"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:04.882387', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-elasticsearch-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"log.message","operator":"filter_match","value":"delete_index OR DeleteIndex OR deleted"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
