 contains("log.message", "dropIndexes") ||
 contains("log.message", "command drop")) &&
exists("origin.host")
', '2026-02-09 16:37:09.477765', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"},{"field":"log.message","operator":"filter_match","value":"drop OR dropDatabase OR dropCollection"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (266, 'MongoDB Injection Attack Patterns', 3, 3, 2, 'Initial Access', 'T1190 - Exploit Public-Facing Application', 'Detects potential MongoDB injection attempts through suspicious query patterns including $where, $function, mapReduce operations, or malicious operators that may contain arbitrary JavaScript code execution. These patterns often indicate attempts to execute code, bypass authentication mechanisms, or perform unauthorized data access.

Next Steps:
- Review the source IP address and check if it''s from a known legitimate application or user
- Examine the full query to understand the attempted injection pattern and payload
- Check if the query was successful or resulted in an error response
- Look for other suspicious activities from the same source IP in recent timeframes
- Verify if any sensitive data was accessed, modified, or exfiltrated
- Consider blocking the source IP if confirmed malicious activity
- Review application code for proper input validation and parameterized queries
- Check MongoDB security configuration and access controls
- Monitor for privilege escalation attempts or lateral movement
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/reference/log-messages/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/","https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/v41/4-Web_Application_Security_Testing/07-Input_Validation_Testing/05.6-Testing_for_NoSQL_Injection"]', 'oneOf("log.component", ["QUERY", "COMMAND"]) &&
(contains("log.message", "$where") ||
 contains("log.message", "$function") ||
 (contains("log.message", "mapReduce") && contains("log.message", "function")) ||
 contains("log.message", "db.eval") ||
 (contains("log.message", "function()") && contains("log.message", "return")))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:09.626921', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (267, 'MongoDB Audit Log Disabling Detection', 2, 3, 1, 'Defense Evasion', 'T1562.002 - Impair Defenses: Disable Windows Event Logging', 'Detects attempts to disable or modify MongoDB audit logging configuration. Attackers disable audit logs to operate without leaving traces after gaining access to the database.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if the audit configuration change was authorized
2. Re-enable audit logging immediately if unauthorized
3. Review database activity during the logging gap
4. Check for data access or modifications while auditing was disabled
5. Restrict access to audit configuration parameters
6. Implement alerts for audit log file size or timestamp anomalies
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/core/auditing/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1562/002/"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
(
  (contains("log.message", "setParameter") && contains("log.message", "auditLog")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "auditLog") && contains("log.message", "disabled")) ||
  contains("log.message", "auditAuthorizationSuccess") ||
  (contains("log.message", "setParameter") && contains("log.message", "logLevel") && contains("log.message", "-1")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "shutdown") && contains("log.message", "audit"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:09.791865', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (268, 'MongoDB Rogue Replica Set Reconfiguration Detection', 3, 3, 2, 'Lateral Movement', 'T1210 - Exploitation of Remote Services', 'Detects MongoDB replica set reconfiguration that could indicate injection of rogue replica members. Attackers use rs.reconfig() to add unauthorized nodes that receive copies of all data, enabling exfiltration.

Next Steps:
1. Review the replica set configuration changes
2. Verify all replica set members are authorized
3. Check for any new or unknown member hosts
4. Remove unauthorized replica set members immediately
5. Restrict replSetReconfig to authorized administrator accounts
6. Monitor network connections to all replica set members
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/reference/command/replSetReconfig/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1210/"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
(
  contains("log.message", "replSetReconfig") ||
  contains("log.message", "rs.reconfig") ||
  contains("log.message", "replSetInitiate") ||
  (contains("log.message", "replSet") && contains("log.message", "added member")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "replSet") && contains("log.message", "config change")) ||
  contains("log.message", "replSetStepDown")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:09.922209', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":2}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (269, 'MongoDB Unauthorized Data Export Detection', 3, 1, 1, 'Data Exfiltration', 'T1048 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol', 'Detects unauthorized mongoexport or mongodump operations that could indicate data exfiltration from MongoDB databases. Monitors for bulk data export commands and large result set queries.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user and source host performing the export
2. Verify if the export was part of authorized backup operations
3. Review the exported collections and data sensitivity
4. Check network traffic for data leaving the environment
5. Restrict mongoexport/mongodump access to authorized accounts
6. Implement database access auditing
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/database-tools/mongoexport/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
(
  contains("log.message", "mongoexport") ||
  contains("log.message", "mongodump") ||
  contains("log.message", "mongorestore") ||
  (contains("log.message", "aggregate") && contains("log.message", "$out")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "find") && contains("log.message", "ntoreturn: 0")) ||
  (contains("log.message", "getMore") && regexMatch("log.message", "(?i)cursorid:\\s*[0-9]+.*nreturned:\\s*[0-9]{4,}"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.141416', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"},{"field":"log.message","operator":"filter_match","value":"mongoexport OR mongodump OR getMore"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":5}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (270, 'MongoDB Role Privilege Escalation', 3, 3, 2, 'Privilege Escalation', 'T1078 - Valid Accounts', 'Detects attempts to escalate privileges through role modifications, user creation with elevated privileges, or grant operations that may indicate unauthorized privilege escalation.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user account that performed the privilege escalation operations
2. Review the specific roles and privileges that were granted or modified
3. Check if the user had legitimate authorization to perform these actions
4. Look for any newly created accounts with administrative privileges
5. Review MongoDB audit logs for the complete sequence of commands executed
6. Check for any suspicious database operations following the privilege changes
7. Verify if similar privilege escalation attempts occurred on other MongoDB instances
8. Consider revoking unauthorized privilege changes and disabling compromised accounts
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/reference/log-messages/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1078/"]', 'oneOf("log.component", ["ACCESS", "COMMAND"]) &&
(contains("log.message", "createRole") ||
 contains("log.message", "updateRole") ||
 contains("log.message", "grantPrivilegesToRole") ||
 contains("log.message", "grantRolesToRole") ||
 contains("log.message", "grantRolesToUser") ||
 contains("log.message", "createUser") ||
 contains("log.message", "updateUser") ||
 contains("log.message", "db.grantRolesToUser") ||
 contains("log.message", "db.createUser") ||
 contains("log.message", "db.updateUser"))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.291903', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"},{"field":"log.component","operator":"filter_term","value":"ACCESS"}],"or":null,"within":"now-30m","count":5}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (271, 'MongoDB SCRAM Authentication Attack Detection', 3, 2, 1, 'Initial Access', 'T1110 - Brute Force', 'Detects multiple failed SCRAM authentication attempts from the same source IP, indicating potential brute force or credential stuffing attacks against MongoDB database users. SCRAM is MongoDB''s default authentication mechanism and repeated failures suggest systematic credential guessing.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the source IP address and check if it''s a legitimate user or system accessing MongoDB
2. Review the targeted MongoDB user accounts for any signs of compromise or suspicious activity
3. Check if the source IP has attempted authentication against other database or application services
4. Consider temporarily blocking the source IP if the attack is ongoing and confirmed malicious
5. Review MongoDB authentication logs for successful logins from the same source after failed attempts
6. Verify that strong password policies are enforced for MongoDB users and consider requiring password resets for targeted accounts
7. Implement or review account lockout policies, rate limiting, and connection throttling for MongoDB authentication
8. Check MongoDB server logs for any database enumeration activities from the source IP
9. Review network security controls to ensure MongoDB is not unnecessarily exposed to external networks
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/core/security-scram/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1110/"]', 'equals("log.component", "ACCESS") && contains("log.message", "SCRAM") && (contains("log.message", "authentication failed") || contains("log.message", "storedKey mismatch") || contains("log.message", "AuthenticationFailed")) && exists("origin.ip")', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.451833', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"log.component","operator":"filter_term","value":"ACCESS"},{"field":"log.message","operator":"filter_match","value":"authentication failed"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":10}]', '["adversary.ip","target.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (272, 'MongoDB Stored JavaScript Execution', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Detects execution of stored JavaScript functions or server-side JavaScript which could be used for code injection attacks or unauthorized operations.

Next Steps:
1. Review the JavaScript code being executed to determine if it''s legitimate
2. Check the source IP and user account for signs of compromise
3. Audit recent changes to system.js collection for malicious stored procedures
4. Review MongoDB access logs for other suspicious activities from the same source
5. Consider disabling server-side JavaScript execution if not required
6. Implement strict access controls for JavaScript execution privileges
', '["https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/core/server-side-javascript/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'equals("log.component", "COMMAND") && (contains("log.message", "$where") || contains("log.message", "$function") || contains("log.message", "mapReduce") || contains("log.message", "system.js")) && !equals("log.severity", "low")', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.587241', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mongodb-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (273, 'MySQL File System Access Attempts', 3, 2, 1, 'Collection', 'T1005 - Data from Local System', 'Detects attempts to access the file system through MySQL commands which could be used for data exfiltration or to read sensitive files. This includes the use of LOAD DATA INFILE, SELECT INTO OUTFILE/DUMPFILE, LOAD_FILE() function, and attempts to access sensitive system files.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user account executing these commands by checking origin.user and origin.host
2. Review the specific file paths being accessed in the log messages
3. Check if the user has legitimate reasons to access file system functions
4. Verify if secure_file_priv is properly configured to restrict file operations
5. Look for any data exfiltration patterns or attempts to read sensitive configuration files
6. Review database audit logs for other suspicious activities from the same user/host
7. If unauthorized, immediately revoke FILE privilege from the user and investigate further
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/load-data.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1005/"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(
  (contains("log.msg", "LOAD DATA") && contains("log.msg", "INFILE")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "SELECT") && contains("log.msg", "INTO OUTFILE")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "SELECT") && contains("log.msg", "INTO DUMPFILE")) ||
  contains("log.msg", "LOAD_FILE") ||
  contains("log.msg", "secure_file_priv") ||
  contains("log.msg", "FILE privilege") ||
  contains("log.msg", "/etc/passwd") ||
  contains("log.msg", "/proc/") ||
  contains("log.msg", "\\windows\\") ||
  contains("log.msg", "\\system32\\") ||
  equals("log.errorCode", "ER_OPTION_PREVENTS_STATEMENT")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.736378', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (296, 'Osquery Agent Tampering Detected', 2, 3, 3, 'Defense Evasion', 'T1562.001 - Impair Defenses: Disable or Modify Tools', 'Detects when the osquery agent is stopped, uninstalled, or tampered with, which attackers do to prevent detection of their activities on compromised hosts.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if the osquery agent stoppage was planned maintenance
2. Check the host for signs of active compromise
3. Restart the osquery agent and verify configuration integrity
4. Review the osquery configuration for unauthorized changes
5. Check the host for other disabled security tools
6. Investigate the user or process that stopped osquery
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1562/001/","https://osquery.readthedocs.io/en/stable/"]', '(contains("log.message", "osqueryd") || contains("log.message", "osquery")) &&
(contains("log.message", "stopped") || contains("log.message", "killed") ||
 contains("log.message", "uninstalled") || contains("log.message", "removed") ||
 contains("log.message", "shutdown") || contains("log.message", "configuration changed") ||
 contains("log.message", "failed to start") || contains("log.message", "disabled")) &&
!(contains("log.message", "graceful shutdown") && contains("log.message", "upgrade"))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:14.166237', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (274, 'MySQL Audit Log Disabling Detection', 2, 3, 1, 'Defense Evasion', 'T1562.002 - Impair Defenses: Disable Windows Event Logging', 'Detects attempts to disable MySQL audit logging by uninstalling the audit_log plugin, modifying audit log variables, or disabling general/slow query logging. Attackers disable auditing to operate without leaving traces.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if the audit log was intentionally disabled by an authorized administrator
2. Re-enable audit logging immediately if unauthorized
3. Check for recent suspicious database activity during the logging gap
4. Review user permissions and revoke unnecessary SUPER privileges
5. Implement monitoring for audit log status changes
6. Check if any data was accessed or modified while logging was disabled
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/audit-log-installation.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1562/002/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)UNINSTALL\\s+PLUGIN\\s+audit_log") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+audit_log_policy\\s*=\\s*[''\"]?NONE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+general_log\\s*=\\s*(0|OFF)") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+slow_query_log\\s*=\\s*(0|OFF)") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+log_output\\s*=\\s*[''\"]?NONE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)UNINSTALL\\s+PLUGIN\\s+server_audit") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+audit_log_flush\\s*=\\s*(0|OFF)")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:10.891447', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (275, 'MySQL Binary Log Tampering Detection', 1, 3, 2, 'Defense Evasion', 'T1070 - Indicator Removal', 'Detects attempts to tamper with MySQL binary logs through PURGE BINARY LOGS or RESET MASTER commands. Attackers delete binary logs to cover tracks after data manipulation or exfiltration, or to disrupt replication.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user account that executed the binary log manipulation
2. Review recent database changes that may have been covered up
3. Check if replication was impacted by the log deletion
4. Verify if the action was part of authorized maintenance
5. Review backup integrity and availability
6. Restrict SUPER privilege to authorized administrator accounts only
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/purge-binary-logs.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1070/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)PURGE\\s+(BINARY|MASTER)\\s+LOGS") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)RESET\\s+MASTER") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)FLUSH\\s+BINARY\\s+LOGS") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+binlog_format") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+expire_logs_days\\s*=\\s*0") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+sql_log_bin\\s*=\\s*(0|OFF)")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.042042', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":2}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (276, 'MySQL Data Exfiltration via OUTFILE/DUMPFILE', 3, 2, 1, 'Data Exfiltration', 'T1048 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol', 'Detects attempts to exfiltrate data from MySQL using SELECT INTO OUTFILE or SELECT INTO DUMPFILE commands. These commands write query results to files on the server filesystem, which attackers use to extract sensitive data or write web shells.

Next Steps:
1. Review the SQL query to identify what data is being exported
2. Check the target file path for web-accessible directories
3. Verify if any files were successfully written to the filesystem
4. Review the user account permissions (FILE privilege)
5. Remove FILE privilege from non-administrative accounts
6. Check for web shells if files were written to web directories
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/select-into.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SELECT.*INTO\\s+OUTFILE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SELECT.*INTO\\s+DUMPFILE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)LOAD_FILE\\s*\\(") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)INTO\\s+OUTFILE\\s+[''\"]/(var|tmp|etc|www|home)") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)INTO\\s+DUMPFILE\\s+[''\"]/(var|tmp|etc|www|home)")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.216467', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (277, 'MySQL Mass Data Deletion Detection', 1, 3, 3, 'Data Destruction', 'T1485 - Data Destruction', 'Detects mass data deletion operations in MySQL including TRUNCATE TABLE, DROP TABLE, DROP DATABASE, and DELETE without WHERE clauses. These operations can indicate data destruction attacks or ransomware targeting databases.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user account performing the destructive operation
2. Verify if the operation was authorized
3. Check if backup systems are intact and uncompromised
4. Review the scope of data loss and affected tables/databases
5. Initiate data recovery from backups if unauthorized
6. Revoke DROP and DELETE privileges from non-administrative accounts
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/truncate-table.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1485/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)TRUNCATE\\s+(TABLE\\s+)?\\w") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)DROP\\s+TABLE\\s+(IF\\s+EXISTS\\s+)?\\w") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)DROP\\s+DATABASE\\s+(IF\\s+EXISTS\\s+)?\\w") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)DELETE\\s+FROM\\s+\\w+\\s*;") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)DELETE\\s+FROM\\s+\\w+\\s*$")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.371441', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"},{"field":"log.msg","operator":"filter_match","value":"TRUNCATE OR DROP TABLE OR DROP DATABASE OR DELETE FROM"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (278, 'MySQL Rogue Replication Attack Detection', 3, 3, 2, 'Lateral Movement', 'T1210 - Exploitation of Remote Services', 'Detects potential rogue MySQL replication attacks where an attacker sets up unauthorized replication to exfiltrate data or inject malicious changes. Monitors for CHANGE MASTER/REPLICATION SOURCE commands and suspicious replication configuration changes.

Next Steps:
1. Verify the replication configuration change was authorized
2. Check the master/source host address for legitimacy
3. Review replication user account permissions
4. Verify replication channel integrity
5. Check for data that may have been exfiltrated via replication
6. Disable unauthorized replication immediately
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/replication-security.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1210/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CHANGE\\s+MASTER\\s+TO") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CHANGE\\s+REPLICATION\\s+SOURCE\\s+TO") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)START\\s+SLAVE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)START\\s+REPLICA") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)SET\\s+GLOBAL\\s+server_id") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "replication") && contains("log.msg", "error")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "slave") && contains("log.msg", "connected"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.511385', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":2}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (436, 'System Linux: Interactive Terminal Spawned via Perl', 2, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Identifies when a terminal (tty) is spawned via Perl. Attackers may upgrade a simple reverse shell to a fully interactive tty after obtaining initial access to a host.', '["https://attack.mitre.org/tactics/TA0002/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'regexMatch("log.message", "(perl)") && regexMatch("log.message", "(exec \\''/bin/sh\\'';|exec \\''/bin/dash\\'';|exec \\''/bin/bash\\'';)")', '2026-02-09 16:51:29.528037', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (279, 'MySQL Plugin Installation Detection', 3, 3, 3, 'Persistence', 'T1505 - Server Software Component', 'Detects plugin installation attempts in MySQL which could be used for persistence or to extend server functionality maliciously. MySQL plugins can provide backdoor access, enable data exfiltration, or modify server behavior.

Next Steps:
1. Review the plugin name and library file being loaded
2. Verify if this plugin installation was authorized and expected
3. Check the source of the plugin library file (.so/.dll)
4. Review MySQL user privileges and who executed the INSTALL PLUGIN command
5. Examine MySQL general and error logs for related suspicious activities
6. Consider reviewing recently modified files in the MySQL plugin directory
7. If unauthorized, immediately uninstall the plugin and investigate potential compromise
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/server-plugin-loading.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1505/"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(contains("log.msg", "INSTALL PLUGIN") ||
 (contains("log.msg", "plugin") && (contains("log.msg", "loaded") || contains("log.msg", "installed"))) ||
 (contains("log.msg", "library") && contains("log.msg", ".so")) ||
 (contains("log.msg", "library") && contains("log.msg", ".dll")) ||
 contains("log.msg", "UNINSTALL PLUGIN") ||
 equals("log.subsystem", "Plugin") ||
 equals("log.errorCode", "MY-013129"))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.656306', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.msg","adversary.host"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (280, 'MySQL Privilege Escalation Attempt', 3, 3, 2, 'Privilege Escalation', 'T1078 - Valid Accounts', 'Detects attempts to escalate privileges in MySQL through GRANT statements, role modifications, or exploitation of FILE privileges. This rule monitors for:
- GRANT statements with dangerous privileges (ALL PRIVILEGES, SUPER, FILE)
- User creation and modification with elevated privileges
- Attempts to access system files through FILE privileges
- Direct manipulation of mysql.user table
- UDF (User Defined Function) creation attempts
- Access denied errors related to privilege operations

Next Steps:
1. Identify the source of the privilege escalation attempt (user, IP, application)
2. Review the MySQL user''s legitimate access requirements
3. Check MySQL audit logs for any successful privilege changes
4. Verify if the user has been granted new privileges: SHOW GRANTS FOR ''username''@''host''
5. Review recent changes to mysql.user table
6. If malicious, revoke unnecessary privileges immediately
7. Consider enabling MySQL audit plugin for enhanced monitoring
8. Review application code for hardcoded credentials or SQL injection vulnerabilities
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/privilege-system.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1078/","https://legalhackers.com/advisories/MySQL-Exploit-Remote-Root-Code-Execution-Privesc-CVE-2016-6662.html"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(
  (contains("log.msg", "GRANT") && (contains("log.msg", "ALL PRIVILEGES") || contains("log.msg", "SUPER") || contains("log.msg", "FILE") || contains("log.msg", "WITH GRANT OPTION"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "CREATE USER") && contains("log.msg", "IDENTIFIED")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "ALTER USER") && (contains("log.msg", "SUPER") || contains("log.msg", "FILE"))) ||
  contains("log.msg", "SET ROLE") ||
  contains("log.msg", "LOAD DATA INFILE") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "SELECT") && contains("log.msg", "INTO OUTFILE") && contains("log.msg", "/etc/")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.user") && (contains("log.msg", "UPDATE") || contains("log.msg", "INSERT"))) ||
  contains("log.msg", "FLUSH PRIVILEGES") ||
  equals("log.errorCode", "ER_SPECIFIC_ACCESS_DENIED_ERROR") ||
  (equals("log.errorCode", "ER_ACCESS_DENIED_ERROR") && contains("log.msg", "SUPER")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "UDF") && (contains("log.msg", "CREATE FUNCTION") || contains("log.msg", "lib_mysqludf_sys")))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.792119', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"},{"field":"log.thread","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{log.thread}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-5m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (281, 'SQL Injection Attempts Detected', 3, 3, 2, 'Initial Access', 'T1190 - Exploit Public-Facing Application', 'Detects potential SQL injection attempts through error messages indicating syntax errors, unauthorized access attempts, or suspicious SQL patterns in MySQL logs. SQL injection attacks can lead to unauthorized data access, data modification, or complete database compromise.

Next Steps:
1. Review the SQL query and error message to confirm if this is a legitimate SQL injection attempt
2. Identify the source IP/host making the suspicious queries
3. Check application logs for corresponding web requests that may have triggered these queries
4. Review other recent queries from the same source for additional suspicious activity
5. If confirmed as malicious, block the source IP at the firewall/WAF level
6. Review and patch the vulnerable application code that allowed the injection
7. Consider implementing prepared statements and input validation in the affected application
8. Monitor database access logs for any unauthorized data access or modifications
9. Review database user permissions and remove unnecessary privileges
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/error-log-format.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/","https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/SQL_Injection"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  contains("log.msg", "1=1") ||
  contains("log.msg", "'' OR ''") ||
  contains("log.msg", "\" OR \"") ||
  contains("log.msg", "'' OR 1") ||
  contains("log.msg", "xp_cmdshell") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "UNION") && contains("log.msg", "SELECT") && contains("log.msg", "FROM")) ||
  contains("log.msg", "INTO OUTFILE") ||
  contains("log.msg", "INTO DUMPFILE") ||
  contains("log.msg", "LOAD_FILE") ||
  contains("log.msg", "BENCHMARK(") ||
  contains("log.msg", "SLEEP(") ||
  contains("log.msg", "WAITFOR DELAY") ||
  contains("log.msg", "@@version") ||
  contains("log.msg", "user()") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "UNION") && contains("log.msg", "information_schema"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:11.921977', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":5}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (282, 'MySQL Trigger Manipulation Detection', 2, 3, 2, 'Persistence', 'T1505.001 - SQL Stored Procedures', 'Detects attempts to create, alter, or drop database triggers which could be used for persistence, data tampering, or privilege escalation. Triggers can execute malicious code automatically on data changes and represent a significant security risk when manipulated by unauthorized users.

Next Steps:
1. Review the trigger manipulation commands in the alert details to understand what changes were attempted
2. Identify the user account that executed the trigger commands and verify if this activity was authorized
3. Examine the trigger definition for any suspicious or malicious code patterns, including calls to external functions or file operations
4. Check for any recent privilege escalations or account compromises for the executing user
5. Review database audit logs for other suspicious activities from the same source IP and user account
6. Verify if the trigger creation aligns with scheduled maintenance or authorized database changes
7. If unauthorized, immediately revoke the user''s trigger creation privileges and audit all existing triggers for malicious content
8. Consider implementing stricter database access controls and trigger creation policies with approval workflows
9. Monitor for subsequent database activities that might leverage the newly created or modified triggers
10. Document the incident and update security procedures to prevent similar unauthorized trigger manipulations
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/trigger-syntax.html","https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/audit-log-reference.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1505/001/"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(
  contains("log.msg", "CREATE TRIGGER") ||
  contains("log.msg", "create trigger") ||
  contains("log.msg", "ALTER TRIGGER") ||
  contains("log.msg", "alter trigger") ||
  contains("log.msg", "DROP TRIGGER") ||
  contains("log.msg", "drop trigger") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "trigger") && contains("log.msg", "definer"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:12.066925', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (437, 'System Linux: Interactive Terminal Spawned via Python', 3, 2, 3, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Identifies when a terminal (tty) is spawned via Python. Attackers may upgrade a simple reverse shell to a fully interactive tty after obtaining initial access to a host.', '["https://attack.mitre.org/tactics/TA0002/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'contains("log.message", "python") && regexMatch("log.message", "(import pty; pty.spawn\\(\\''\\/bin\\/(sh|dash|bash)\\''\\))")', '2026-02-09 16:51:29.687221', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (283, 'MySQL Stored Procedure Abuse', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Detects potential abuse of stored procedures and functions including creation of malicious procedures, execution of system commands, or unauthorized procedure modifications. This could indicate an attacker attempting to establish persistence, execute arbitrary commands, or escalate privileges within the MySQL database.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the user account that executed the suspicious stored procedure operation
2. Review the full SQL statement to understand the intent and potential impact
3. Check if the stored procedure/function name follows organizational naming conventions
4. Verify if the user has legitimate reasons to create/modify stored procedures
5. Look for any unusual DEFINER clauses that could indicate privilege escalation attempts
6. Review recent authentication logs for the user to check for compromised credentials
7. If malicious, immediately revoke the user''s stored procedure privileges
8. Audit all stored procedures created or modified by this user
9. Check for any data exfiltration or unauthorized access that may have occurred
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/stored-programs-defining.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/","https://www.mysql.com/products/enterprise/audit.html"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(
  (contains("log.msg", "CREATE PROCEDURE") && (contains("log.msg", "xp_cmdshell") || contains("log.msg", "sys_exec") || contains("log.msg", "sys_eval"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "CREATE FUNCTION") && (contains("log.msg", "SONAME") || contains("log.msg", ".so") || contains("log.msg", ".dll"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "CALL") && (contains("log.msg", "sys.") || contains("log.msg", "mysql."))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.proc") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE") || contains("log.msg", "DELETE"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.func") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE"))) ||
  contains("log.msg", "lib_mysqludf") ||
  equals("log.errorCode", "ER_PROCACCESS_DENIED_ERROR")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:12.202043', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (284, 'MySQL UDF Exploitation Attempts', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Detects attempts to create or use User Defined Functions (UDFs) in MySQL which could be used for privilege escalation or code execution. UDFs allow execution of arbitrary code through the MySQL server process, potentially leading to complete system compromise.

Next Steps:
1. Review the MySQL error logs to identify the source IP and user account attempting UDF operations
2. Check if the UDF libraries (lib_mysqludf_sys, openssl_udf) exist on the MySQL server filesystem
3. Examine MySQL user privileges - only users with CREATE ROUTINE privilege should be able to create functions
4. Review recent authentication logs for the MySQL user account involved
5. Check for any suspicious files in the MySQL plugin directory (typically /usr/lib/mysql/plugin/)
6. Consider revoking CREATE ROUTINE privileges from non-administrative users
7. Enable MySQL audit logging if not already active to capture detailed query information
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/create-function-loadable.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'exists("log.message") && 
((contains("log.message", "CREATE FUNCTION") && (contains("log.message", "SONAME") || contains("log.message", "RETURNS"))) ||
 contains("log.message", "DROP FUNCTION") ||
 contains("log.message", "sys_exec") ||
 contains("log.message", "sys_eval") ||
 contains("log.message", "lib_mysqludf_sys") ||
 contains("log.message", "openssl_udf") ||
 equals("log.errorCode", "ER_CANT_FIND_UDF") ||
 equals("log.errorCode", "ER_CANT_CREATE_UDF") ||
 (contains("log.message", "UDF") && (contains("log.message", "error") || contains("log.message", "failed"))))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:12.362566', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (285, 'MySQL User Account Manipulation', 3, 3, 1, 'Persistence', 'T1098 - Account Manipulation', 'Detects suspicious user account manipulation activities including creation of backdoor accounts, password changes, or unauthorized account modifications in MySQL databases. This could indicate an attacker attempting to establish persistence or elevate privileges.

Next Steps:
1. Review the specific account manipulation activity in the MySQL logs
2. Identify the user account that performed the action and verify if it was authorized
3. Check if the affected user account shows any suspicious privilege grants
4. Review recent authentication logs for the source host
5. Examine if there are any other account manipulation attempts from the same source
6. Consider revoking suspicious accounts and resetting passwords if unauthorized
', '["https://dev.mysql.com/doc/refman/8.0/en/account-management-statements.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1098/"]', 'exists("log.msg") && 
(
  contains("log.msg", "CREATE USER") ||
  contains("log.msg", "DROP USER") ||
  contains("log.msg", "RENAME USER") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "ALTER USER") && (contains("log.msg", "IDENTIFIED BY") || contains("log.msg", "PASSWORD"))) ||
  contains("log.msg", "SET PASSWORD") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "GRANT") && contains("log.msg", "TO") && contains("log.msg", "@")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "REVOKE") && contains("log.msg", "FROM")) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.user") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE") || contains("log.msg", "DELETE"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.db") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.tables_priv") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.columns_priv") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE"))) ||
  (contains("log.msg", "mysql.procs_priv") && (contains("log.msg", "INSERT") || contains("log.msg", "UPDATE"))) ||
  equals("log.errorCode", "ER_CANNOT_USER") ||
  equals("log.errorCode", "ER_PASSWORD_NO_MATCH")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:12.487072', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-mysql-*","with":[{"field":"origin.host","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.host}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (286, 'Nginx FastCGI Exploitation Attempt', 3, 3, 2, 'Initial Access', 'T1190 - Exploit Public-Facing Application', 'Detects FastCGI exploitation attempts including path traversal, SCRIPT_FILENAME injection, and CVE-2019-11043 PHP-FPM/nginx RCE patterns. These attacks can lead to remote code execution and complete server compromise.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately block the source IP at the firewall level
2. Review all nginx access logs from the same IP for additional exploitation attempts
3. Check if the PHP-FPM service is exposed and properly configured
4. Verify nginx configuration for proper FastCGI security settings
5. Look for any signs of successful exploitation (new processes, files, or network connections)
6. Apply security patches for nginx and PHP-FPM if not up to date
7. Consider implementing a Web Application Firewall (WAF) to filter malicious requests
8. Check for any unusual file modifications or new files created on the server
9. Monitor system processes for any suspicious PHP or shell processes
10. Review recent nginx error logs for additional attack indicators
', '["https://nextcloud.com/blog/urgent-security-issue-in-nginx-php-fpm/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1190/"]', '(contains("origin.path", ".php") && regexMatch("origin.path", ".*(\\.\\.[\\/\\\\]|%2e%2e).*")) ||
(contains("log.request", "SCRIPT_FILENAME") && contains("log.request", "../")) ||
(regexMatch("origin.path", ".*\\.php[\\/\\\\].*\\.php.*")) ||
(contains("log.message", "FastCGI sent in stderr") && equals("log.severityLabel", "error")) ||
(contains("origin.path", ".php") && contains("origin.path", "%00")) ||
(regexMatch("log.request", ".*\\.php.*[\\/\\\\]?.*\\?.*=.*\\.php.*")) ||
(equals("log.statusCode", 502) && contains("log.message", "fastcgi")) ||
(contains("log.userAgent", "python") && contains("origin.path", ".php") && greaterOrEqual("log.statusCode", 400))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:12.646464', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-nginx-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":5}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (340, 'Python Reverse Shell Detected', 3, 3, 3, 'Command and Control', 'T1059.006 - Command and Scripting Interpreter: Python', 'Detects Python being used with socket and pty modules to establish a reverse shell. This is a very common post-exploitation technique, particularly after webshell access or application-level compromise. The combination of socket+pty+spawn+connect is a strong indicator of malicious activity.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately isolate the affected host from the network
2. Identify the parent process that spawned Python (web server, cron, etc.)
3. Determine the destination IP and port of the outbound connection
4. Check for webshell files if the parent process is a web server
5. Review Python process arguments and any scripts referenced
6. Search for additional persistence mechanisms on the host
7. Hunt for the same C2 IP across all monitored systems
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/006/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/linux/process_creation/proc_creation_lnx_python_reverse_shell.yml"]', 'exists("log.message") &&
regexMatch("log.message", "(?i)python[23]?\\s+-c\\s+.*socket.*pty.*spawn") &&
contains("log.message", "connect")
', '2026-02-09 16:39:10.341903', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (287, 'Lua Script Injection Attempt', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Detects potential Lua script injection attempts through malicious input patterns in requests that could be processed by Nginx Lua modules, potentially leading to remote code execution.

Next Steps:
1. Review the source IP address and check if it''s known or trusted
2. Examine the full request details to understand the injection attempt
3. Check if your Nginx configuration uses Lua modules (openresty/lua-nginx-module)
4. Review Nginx error logs for any script execution errors
5. Block the source IP if confirmed malicious
6. Update WAF rules to prevent similar injection attempts
