Next Steps:
1. Review the request parameters for template injection payloads
2. Identify the backend template engine being targeted
3. Check if any payloads were successfully rendered
4. Implement input sanitization and template sandboxing
5. Block the source IP if confirmed malicious
6. Review application code for unsafe template rendering
', '["https://portswigger.net/research/server-side-template-injection","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'exists("origin.ip") &&
exists("origin.path") &&
(
  regexMatch("origin.path", "(?i)\\{\\{[0-9]+\\*[0-9]+\\}\\}") ||
  regexMatch("origin.path", "(?i)\\$\\{[0-9]+\\*[0-9]+\\}") ||
  contains("origin.path", "{{config") ||
  contains("origin.path", "{{self") ||
  contains("origin.path", "__class__") ||
  contains("origin.path", "__import__") ||
  contains("origin.path", "__builtins__") ||
  contains("origin.path", "__subclasses__") ||
  contains("origin.path", "${T(java.lang") ||
  contains("origin.path", "#{T(java.lang") ||
  contains("origin.path", "${Runtime") ||
  contains("origin.path", "{{request.application")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:13.736820', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-nginx-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"origin.path","operator":"filter_match","value":"__class__ OR __import__ OR Runtime OR __subclasses__"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":3}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (294, 'Nginx Web Shell Access Detection', 3, 3, 2, 'Persistence', 'T1505.003 - Server Software Component: Web Shell', 'Detects access to known web shell paths through Nginx. Monitors for requests to common web shell filenames, suspicious PHP/JSP file access with command parameters, and successful responses to known malicious paths.

Next Steps:
1. Investigate the accessed file on the web server immediately
2. Check file contents for malicious code patterns
3. Review file creation/modification timestamps
4. Scan the entire web directory for additional web shells
5. Check for post-exploitation activity from the server
6. Remove the web shell and patch the vulnerability
', '["https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/security/blog/2021/02/11/web-shell-attacks-continue-to-rise/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1505/003/"]', 'exists("origin.ip") &&
exists("origin.path") &&
(
  regexMatch("origin.path", "(?i)/(c99|r57|b374k|alfa|wso|mini|phpspy|shell|cmd|eval|backdoor)\\.(php|jsp|asp|aspx)") ||
  regexMatch("origin.path", "(?i)\\.(php|jsp|asp|aspx|phtml)\\?(cmd|exec|command|shell|c|e|id|pass|action)=") ||
  contains("origin.path", "/webshell") ||
  contains("origin.path", "/adminer.php") ||
  contains("origin.path", "/phpinfo.php") ||
  contains("origin.path", "/.well-known/") ||
  regexMatch("origin.path", "(?i)/wp-content/(uploads|plugins|themes)/.*\\.(php|phtml)")
) &&
greaterOrEqual("log.statusCode", 200) &&
lessThan("log.statusCode", 400)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:13.866217', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.path"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (295, 'Fleet/Kolide Server Compromise Indicators', 3, 3, 3, 'Initial Access', 'T1199 - Trusted Relationship', 'Detects indicators of Fleet or Kolide osquery management server compromise, including unauthorized configuration pushes, enrollment tampering, and suspicious distributed query execution that could affect all managed endpoints.

Next Steps:
1. Verify the Fleet/Kolide server integrity
2. Check for unauthorized admin access to the management console
3. Review recent configuration changes and distributed queries
4. Audit enrollment certificates and TLS configuration
5. Check for unauthorized user accounts on the management server
6. If compromised, rotate all enrollment secrets and re-enroll agents
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1199/"]', '(contains("log.message", "fleet") || contains("log.message", "kolide") ||
 contains("log.message", "enrollment")) &&
(contains("log.message", "unauthorized") || contains("log.message", "invalid certificate") ||
 (contains("log.message", "enrollment secret") && contains("log.message", "changed")) ||
 contains("log.message", "TLS error") || contains("log.message", "certificate mismatch") ||
 (contains("log.message", "configuration changed") && contains("log.message", "remote")))
', '2026-02-09 16:37:14.006753', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.host","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (297, 'PostgreSQL COPY TO/FROM PROGRAM RCE Detection', 3, 3, 3, 'Code Execution', 'T1005 - Data from Local System', 'Detects use of PostgreSQL COPY TO/FROM PROGRAM for remote command execution. This feature allows superusers to execute arbitrary system commands through the database, which attackers exploit after gaining superuser access.

Next Steps:
1. Identify the database user executing the COPY PROGRAM command
2. Review the system command being executed
3. Check for signs of compromise on the database server
4. Verify if the action was part of authorized database operations
5. Restrict COPY PROGRAM access to essential superuser accounts only
6. Review pg_hba.conf for overly permissive access rules
', '["https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-copy.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1005/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)COPY\\s+.*\\s+(TO|FROM)\\s+PROGRAM") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)COPY\\s+\\(.*\\)\\s+TO\\s+PROGRAM") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "COPY") && contains("log.msg", "PROGRAM") && (
    contains("log.msg", "/bin/") ||
    contains("log.msg", "bash") ||
    contains("log.msg", "curl") ||
    contains("log.msg", "wget") ||
    contains("log.msg", "python") ||
    contains("log.msg", "perl") ||
    contains("log.msg", "nc ") ||
    contains("log.msg", "ncat")
  ))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:14.327001', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.sessionId","adversary.host"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (298, 'PostgreSQL dblink Exfiltration Detection', 3, 2, 1, 'Data Exfiltration', 'T1048 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol', 'Detects use of dblink_connect to establish connections to external database servers for data exfiltration. Attackers use dblink to transfer data from compromised databases to attacker-controlled servers.

Next Steps:
1. Review the dblink connection string for the target server
2. Verify if the external connection was authorized
3. Check what queries were executed through dblink
4. Remove the dblink extension if not needed
5. Implement network-level restrictions on outbound database connections
6. Audit database extensions and revoke unnecessary permissions
', '["https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/dblink.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)dblink_connect\\s*\\(") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)dblink\\s*\\(") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)dblink_exec\\s*\\(") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+EXTENSION\\s+(IF\\s+NOT\\s+EXISTS\\s+)?dblink") ||
  (contains("log.msg", "dblink") && regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)host(addr)?\\s*=\\s*[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:14.491302', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.sessionId","adversary.host"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (299, 'PostgreSQL Extension-Based RCE Detection', 3, 3, 3, 'Code Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Detects creation of PostgreSQL extensions that enable code execution such as plpythonu, plperlu, plsh, or pljava. Attackers use these procedural language extensions to execute arbitrary system commands through the database.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if the extension installation was authorized
2. Identify the user account that created the extension
3. Check for any functions created using the dangerous extension
4. Review pg_extension catalog for unauthorized extensions
5. Remove unauthorized extensions immediately
6. Restrict CREATE EXTENSION privileges
', '["https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/sql-createextension.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+EXTENSION\\s+(IF\\s+NOT\\s+EXISTS\\s+)?(plpythonu|plpython2u|plpython3u|plperlu|plsh|pljava|plr|plruby)") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+(OR\\s+REPLACE\\s+)?FUNCTION.*LANGUAGE\\s+(plpythonu|plpython2u|plpython3u|plperlu|plsh|pljava)") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+EXTENSION.*adminpack") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)LOAD\\s+[''\"].*\\.(so|dll)[''\"]")
)
', '2026-02-09 16:37:14.731310', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.sessionId","adversary.host"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (300, 'PostgreSQL Foreign Data Wrapper Exfiltration Detection', 3, 2, 1, 'Data Exfiltration', 'T1048 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol', 'Detects abuse of PostgreSQL Foreign Data Wrappers (FDW) for data exfiltration. Attackers create foreign servers pointing to external systems to transfer data out of the database through SQL queries.

Next Steps:
1. Review the foreign server and user mapping configurations
2. Verify the external server address is legitimate
3. Check what data is accessible through the foreign tables
4. Remove unauthorized foreign servers and user mappings
5. Restrict CREATE SERVER and CREATE FOREIGN TABLE privileges
6. Monitor network connections from the database server
', '["https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/postgres-fdw.html","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/"]', 'exists("log.msg") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+SERVER\\s+\\w+\\s+FOREIGN\\s+DATA\\s+WRAPPER") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+FOREIGN\\s+TABLE") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+USER\\s+MAPPING\\s+FOR") ||
  regexMatch("log.msg", "(?i)CREATE\\s+EXTENSION\\s+(IF\\s+NOT\\s+EXISTS\\s+)?postgres_fdw") ||
