Next Steps:
1. Identify the internal host connecting to mining pools
2. Scan the host for mining malware (XMRig, CGMiner, etc.)
3. Review CPU/GPU utilization on the affected host
4. Check how the mining software was installed (vulnerability, phishing, insider)
5. Remove the mining software and patch the entry vector
6. Block mining pool ports at the network perimeter
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1496/","https://www.cisco.com/en/US/technologies/tk648/tk362/technologies_white_paper09186a00800a3db9.html"]', 'exists("origin.ip") &&
exists("target.ip") &&
oneOf("target.port", [3333, 4444, 5555, 7777, 8888, 9999, 14444, 14433, 45560]) &&
equals("protocol", "TCP") &&
!inCIDR("target.ip", "10.0.0.0/8") &&
!inCIDR("target.ip", "172.16.0.0/12") &&
!inCIDR("target.ip", "192.168.0.0/16")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:25.972958', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-netflow-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-30m","count":5}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
