!inCIDR("target.ip", "192.168.0.0/16")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:26.987216', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-netflow-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"target.port","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{target.port}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-1h","count":3}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip","target.port"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (497, 'Tor Network Usage Detection', 3, 2, 1, 'Command and Control', 'T1090 - Proxy: Multi-hop Proxy', 'Detects potential Tor network usage based on connections to known Tor entry node ports (9001, 9030, 9050, 9051) and traffic patterns consistent with Tor usage. Tor is commonly used by attackers to anonymize their traffic and evade detection.

Next Steps:
1. Verify if Tor usage is authorized in your organization''s security policy
2. Investigate the source IP address and user context if available
3. Check for other suspicious activities from the same source
4. Consider blocking Tor traffic if not authorized for business use
5. Review firewall logs for additional Tor-related connections
6. Correlate with authentication logs to identify the user if possible
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1090/","https://www.cisco.com/en/US/technologies/tk648/tk362/technologies_white_paper09186a00800a3db9.html","https://www.torproject.org/"]', 'exists("origin.ip") && exists("target.ip") &&
oneOf("target.port", [9001, 9030, 9050, 9051]) &&
equals("protocol", "6") && greaterThan("log.bytes", 512)
', '2026-02-09 16:52:27.132413', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-netflow-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-1h","count":5}]', '["adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (671, 'Windows: Execution via MSSQL xp_cmdshell Stored Procedure', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1059 - Command and Scripting Interpreter', 'Identifies execution via MSSQL xp_cmdshell stored procedure. Malicious users may attempt to elevate their privileges by using xp_cmdshell, which is disabled by default, thus, it''s important to review the context of it''s use.', '["https://attack.mitre.org/tactics/TA0002/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1059/"]', 'oneOf("log.message", ["diskfree", "rmdir", "mkdir", "dir", "del", "rename", "bcp", "XMLNAMESPACES"]) && contains("log.winlogEventDataProcessName", "cmd.exe") && contains("log.winlogEventDataParentProcessName", "sqlservr.exe")', '2026-02-09 16:57:25.311986', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (499, 'Base64-Encoded DNS Query Detected', 3, 2, 1, 'Exfiltration', 'T1048.003 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol: Exfiltration Over Unencrypted Non-C2 Protocol', 'Detects DNS queries containing base64-encoded data, identified by the presence of ''=='' padding followed by a dot separator. This pattern is commonly used in DNS-based data exfiltration where stolen data is encoded in base64 and split across DNS query subdomains. Legitimate DNS queries almost never contain base64 padding characters.

Next Steps:
1. Decode the base64 content from the DNS query subdomains
2. Identify what data is being exfiltrated through the DNS channel
3. Isolate the source host generating these queries
4. Block the DNS domain being used for exfiltration at the resolver
5. Review the volume and frequency of these queries to assess data loss
6. Check for malware on the source host that is performing the exfiltration
7. Implement DNS query length monitoring and blocking for oversized queries
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/003/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/network/dns/net_dns_susp_b64_queries.yml"]', 'equals("log.eventType", "dns") &&
exists("log.dns.query") &&
regexMatch("log.dns.query", ".*==\\..*") &&
exists("origin.ip")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:27.413211', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"log.eventType","operator":"filter_term","value":"dns"}],"or":null,"within":"now-10m","count":5}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (500, 'Base64-Encoded User Agent String Detected', 2, 2, 1, 'Command and Control', 'T1071.001 - Application Layer Protocol: Web Protocols', 'Detects HTTP traffic where the user agent string appears to be a base64-encoded value. Some malware families (notably YamaBot/Torisma attributed to North Korean APT Lazarus) use base64-encoded browser strings as user agents. This evasion technique attempts to bypass user agent-based detection while still being identifiable by the base64 encoding pattern.

Next Steps:
1. Decode the base64 user agent string to identify the encoded content
2. Investigate the source host for malware, particularly Lazarus/DPRK-attributed tools
3. Check the destination for known C2 infrastructure
4. Correlate with other suspicious activity from the same host
5. Block the destination IP/domain at the network perimeter
6. Perform endpoint forensics to identify the malware component
7. Search for similar base64-encoded UA patterns from other hosts
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1071/001/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/proxy_generic/proxy_ua_base64_encoded.yml"]', 'equals("log.eventType", "http") &&
exists("log.http.http_user_agent") &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
regexMatch("log.http.http_user_agent", "^[A-Za-z0-9+/]{40,}={0,2}$")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:27.562596', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"log.eventType","operator":"filter_term","value":"http"}],"or":null,"within":"now-30m","count":3}]', '["lastEvent.log.http.http_user_agent","adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (501, 'Cobalt Strike DNS Beacon Pattern Detected', 3, 3, 2, 'Command and Control', 'T1071.004 - Application Layer Protocol: DNS', 'Detects DNS queries matching known Cobalt Strike DNS beacon patterns. Cobalt Strike uses specific DNS query prefixes for its DNS-based C2 channel, including ''aaa.stage.'' for staging and ''post.1'' for data exfiltration. These patterns are highly specific to Cobalt Strike and rarely appear in legitimate DNS traffic.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately isolate the source host generating these DNS queries
2. Capture and analyze the full DNS query/response pairs for encoded C2 data
3. Search for the Cobalt Strike beacon payload on the affected endpoint
4. Check for lateral movement from the compromised system
5. Block the identified C2 domains at the DNS resolver level
6. Perform memory forensics on the endpoint to identify the beacon configuration
7. Review network logs for additional C2 channels (HTTP/HTTPS beacons)
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1071/004/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/network/dns/net_dns_mal_cobaltstrike.yml","https://blog.sekoia.io/hunting-and-detecting-cobalt-strike/"]', 'equals("log.eventType", "dns") &&
exists("log.dns.query") &&
(
  regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)^aaa\\.stage\\.") ||
  regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)^post\\.1") ||
  (regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)^cdn\\.") && regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)\\.(stage|post)\\.")) ||
  (regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)^api\\.") && regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)\\.(stage|post)\\.")) ||
  (regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)^www6\\.") && regexMatch("log.dns.query", "(?i)\\.(stage|post)\\."))
) &&
exists("origin.ip")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:27.712837', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"log.eventType","operator":"filter_term","value":"dns"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":3}]', '["lastEvent.log.dns.query","adversary.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (502, 'Cobalt Strike Malleable C2 Profile Detected', 3, 3, 2, 'Command and Control', 'T1071.001 - Application Layer Protocol: Web Protocols', 'Detects HTTP traffic patterns matching known Cobalt Strike malleable C2 profiles. Cobalt Strike operators use malleable C2 profiles to disguise their C2 traffic as legitimate services (Amazon, OCSP, OneDrive, jQuery). This rule matches specific URI patterns, HTTP headers, and user agent combinations that are characteristic of common malleable C2 profiles.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately isolate the source host from the network
2. Capture full packet data for the identified C2 sessions
3. Perform memory forensics to extract the beacon configuration
4. Identify the C2 server infrastructure and block at network perimeter
5. Search for additional compromised hosts communicating with the same infrastructure
6. Check for lateral movement and credential theft from the compromised host
7. Engage incident response procedures for confirmed C2 activity
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1071/001/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/proxy_generic/proxy_hktl_cobalt_strike_malleable_c2_requests.yml","https://www.cobaltstrike.com/help-malleable-c2"]', 'equals("log.eventType", "http") &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
exists("target.ip") &&
(
  (contains("log.http.url", "/s/ref=nb_sb_noss_1/") && contains("log.http.http_user_agent", "Mozilla")) ||
  (contains("log.http.url", "/MFEwTzBNMEswSTAJBg") && contains("log.http.http_content_type", "application/ocsp-response")) ||
  (regexMatch("log.http.url", "(?i)/jquery-3\\.[0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.min\\.js$") && contains("log.http.http_user_agent", "Mozilla")) ||
  (contains("log.http.url", "/_api/v2.0/") && contains("log.http.hostname", "onedrive")) ||
  (contains("log.http.url", "/pixel.gif") && contains("log.http.url", "utmac=")) ||
  (regexMatch("log.http.url", "(?i)/api/v1/push$") && contains("log.http.http_content_type", "application/octet-stream")) ||
  (contains("log.http.url", "/updates/") && endsWith("log.http.url", ".cab")) ||
  (regexMatch("log.http.url", "(?i)/__utm\\.gif\\?utmac=") && contains("log.http.http_user_agent", "Mozilla"))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:52:27.848465', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"target.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{target.ip}}"},{"field":"log.eventType","operator":"filter_term","value":"http"}],"or":null,"within":"now-30m","count":3}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (681, 'Windows: Multiple remote access login failures', 3, 2, 2, 'Credential Access', 'T1110 - Brute Force', 'Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained.', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1110/"]', 'oneOf("log.eventCode", [20187, 20014, 20078, 20050, 20049, 2018]) &&
regexMatch("log.message", "(?i)(authentication failed|login failed|access denied|authentication error|invalid credentials)")
', '2026-02-09 16:57:26.752360', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-wineventlog-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":10}]', '["adversary.ip","adversary.user"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (504, 'Covert Channel Detection', 3, 2, 1, 'Exfiltration', 'Covert Channel Communication', 'Detects potential covert channel communication through unusual protocols, DNS tunneling, or ICMP data exfiltration patterns. This rule identifies suspicious network communications that may be used to bypass security controls and exfiltrate data through legitimate-looking traffic.

Next Steps:
1. Examine the source and destination IPs involved in the communication
2. Analyze the DNS queries for suspicious patterns, encoding, or unusual subdomain structures
3. Review ICMP traffic payload sizes and patterns for data hiding indicators
4. Check for base64 encoded data in DNS queries or other protocols
5. Correlate with endpoint security logs to identify the source process or application
6. Monitor for similar patterns from the same source IP over extended time periods
7. Consider network traffic analysis to identify covert communication protocols
8. Review firewall and proxy logs for blocked or allowed suspicious connections
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/","https://docs.suricata.io/en/latest/output/eve/eve-json-format.html"]', '(
  (equals("log.eventType", "alert") &&
   contains("log.alert.signature", "DNS tunneling")) ||
  (equals("protocol", "ICMP") &&
   greaterThan("log.flow.bytes_toserver", 1000)) ||
  (equals("protocol", "DNS") &&
   greaterThan("log.dns.query.length", 100)) ||
  (equals("log.appProto", "dns") &&
   contains("log.dns.query.rrname", ".base64."))
)
', '2026-02-09 16:52:28.137680', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-1h","count":10}]', '["adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (505, 'Data Exfiltration Pattern Detection', 3, 1, 1, 'Exfiltration', 'T1048 - Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol', 'Detects potential data exfiltration activities through unusual outbound traffic patterns, large data transfers, suspicious protocols, base64 encoded data, and connections to external file sharing services. This rule identifies various indicators of data theft including large uploads, connections to file sharing services, DNS tunneling, and TOR usage.

Next Steps:
1. Investigate the source host for signs of compromise or unauthorized access
2. Review network logs to identify the exact data being transferred
3. Check if the destination is a known legitimate service or suspicious domain
4. Examine user activity on the source system for unauthorized data access
5. Review file access logs and recently modified sensitive files
6. Analyze DNS queries for potential data tunneling patterns
7. Check for presence of data collection tools or scripts on the affected system
8. Verify if the large data transfer was authorized by business processes
9. Consider implementing additional monitoring on the affected host
10. If confirmed malicious, isolate the affected system and begin incident response procedures
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1048/","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1041/","https://www.snort.org/rule_docs/"]', '(contains("log.alert.signature", ["exfiltration", "data theft", "suspicious upload"]) ||
 oneOf("log.alert.category", ["policy-violation", "data-loss"]) ||
