Next Steps:
1. Immediately investigate the source IP and target system for signs of compromise
2. Review the specific CVE or vulnerability signature that triggered the alert
3. Check if the target system has been patched against the detected vulnerability
4. Analyze network traffic patterns around the time of the alert for additional suspicious activity
5. Verify if the exploit attempt was successful by checking system logs and file integrity
6. Consider blocking the source IP if confirmed malicious
7. Review and update security controls to prevent similar exploit attempts
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1210/","https://www.snort.org/rule_docs/"]', '(contains("log.alert.signature", ["exploit", "overflow", "shellcode", "CVE-"]) ||
 oneOf("log.alert.category", ["attempted-admin", "attempted-user", "shellcode-detect"])) &&
exists("origin.ip") &&
equals("log.eventType", "alert")
', '2026-02-09 16:52:29.058325', true, false, 'origin', null, '[{"indexPattern":"v11-log-suricata-*","with":[{"field":"origin.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{origin.ip}}"},{"field":"target.ip","operator":"filter_term","value":"{{target.ip}}"}],"or":null,"within":"now-15m","count":3}]', '["lastEvent.log.alert.signature","adversary.ip","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (536, 'WildFire Malware Detection', 3, 3, 2, 'Execution', 'T1204.002 - User Execution: Malicious File', 'Detects when WildFire identifies malicious files or malware based on threat analysis. This rule triggers on files with malicious verdicts from WildFire''s advanced analysis engine, indicating potential malware execution or file-based threats.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately isolate the affected host to prevent lateral movement
2. Review the file hash and name from the WildFire report
3. Check if the file was executed or just downloaded
4. Investigate user activity around the time of detection
5. Scan other systems for the same file hash
6. Review email logs if the file came via email attachment
7. Update security policies to prevent similar threats
8. Consider forensic analysis of the affected system
', '["https://docs.paloaltonetworks.com/advanced-wildfire/administration/advanced-wildfire-overview","https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1204/002/"]', 'equals("log.pa_type", "THREAT") && equals("log.pa_subtype", "wildfire") && oneOf("log.severityLabel", ["high", "critical"]) && oneOf("log.act", ["alert", "block", "deny"])', '2026-02-09 16:53:33.007425', true, false, 'origin', null, '[]', '["lastEvent.log.pa_threatid","target.host","target.ip"]');
insert into public.utm_correlation_rules (id, rule_name, rule_confidentiality, rule_integrity, rule_availability, rule_category, rule_technique, rule_description, rule_references_def, rule_definition_def, rule_last_update, rule_active, system_owner, rule_adversary, rule_deduplicate_by_def, rule_after_events_def, rule_group_by_def) values (512, 'Exploit Framework User Agent Detected in HTTP Traffic', 3, 3, 2, 'Command and Control', 'T1071.001 - Application Layer Protocol: Web Protocols', 'Detects HTTP traffic containing user agent strings from known C2 frameworks and exploit tools including Cobalt Strike, Metasploit, Empire, Havoc, Sliver, Brute Ratel, Mythic, and other offensive security frameworks. These user agents are strong indicators of active command and control communication or exploitation attempts.

Next Steps:
1. Immediately isolate the source host generating this traffic
2. Determine which C2 framework is in use based on the specific user agent
3. Perform endpoint forensics to locate the implant/beacon
4. Block the destination IP/domain at the network perimeter
5. Search for other hosts communicating with the same C2 infrastructure
6. Check for data exfiltration and lateral movement from the compromised host
7. Engage incident response for confirmed C2 compromise
', '["https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1071/001/","https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma/blob/master/rules/web/proxy_generic/proxy_ua_frameworks.yml"]', 'equals("log.eventType", "http") &&
